SIMPLE: franchise
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Franchise
<hw>Fran"chise</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.,
fr. <ets>franc</ets>, fem. <ets>franche</ets>, free. See <er>Frank</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Exemption from constraint or
oppression; freedom; liberty.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(LAw)</fld> <def>A particular privilege conferred by
grant from a sovereign or a government, and vested in individuals; an
immunity or exemption from ordinary jurisdiction; a constitutional or
statutory right or privilege, esp. the right to vote.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Election by universal suffrage, as modified by the Constitution,
is the one crowning <qex>franchise</qex> of the American people.</q>
<rj><qau>W. H. Seward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The district or jurisdiction to which a particular
privilege extends; the limits of an immunity; hence, an asylum or
sanctuary.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Churches and mobasteries in Spain are <qex>franchises</qex> for
criminals.</q> <rj><qau>London Encyc.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Magnanimity; generosity; liberality; frankness;
nobility.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Franchise</xex> in woman.⟦rdquo⟧
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Elective franchise</b></col>, <cd>the privilege or right
of voting in an election of public officers.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Franchise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Franchise
<hw>Fran"chise</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Franchised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Franchising</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>franchir</ets>
to free, F., to cross.]</ety> <def>To make free; to enfranchise; to give
liberty to.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Franchisement</ent>⟦br⟧
